# C# control-flow layout (no braces for single statements)

Omit braces when the body is **exactly one statement**. Place that statement on the **same line** or the **next line** using the rules below.

## Line placement

1. **Action is short enough** — put it on the **same line** as the condition:

```csharp
if (condition) return null;
else if (other) throw new ArgumentException("...");
else DoFallback();
```

2. **Action is too long for one line** — put it on the **next line**, indented (still no braces):

```csharp
else
    await _eventPublisher.PublishAsync(
        RedisEventChannels.UserNicknameChanged,
        new UserNicknameChangedEvent(user.Id, user.Nickname, IsDeleted: false, DateTimeOffset.UtcNow));
```

3. **Condition is too long for a same-line action** — put the action on the **next line**, even when the action itself is short:

```csharp
if (await _userBlockService.IsBlockedByAsync(userId, otherUserId)
    || await _userBlockService.IsBlockedByAsync(otherUserId, userId))
    throw new ArgumentException("Cannot chat while a block exists between you and this user.");
```

## Combined example

```csharp
if (isReady) return Ok();
else if (isPending) return Accepted();
else if (await Service.IsBlockedByAsync(userId, otherUserId)
    || await Service.IsBlockedByAsync(otherUserId, userId))
    throw new ArgumentException("Blocked.");
else
    return BadRequest("Email and password are required.");
```

## Use braces only when

- The body has **two or more** statements.
- Nesting would be ambiguous without braces.

```csharp
if (condition)
{
    await DoWorkAsync();
    return;
}
```

## When editing

- **New code**: follow the three line-placement rules; default to braceless single statements.
- **Existing code**: match the surrounding method; do not mass-reformat unrelated style.
- **Do not apply** in `services/Api/Migrations/` (generated EF code).

`RCS1001` is suppressed in `.editorconfig` for this style.
